Qt module:   qtmultimedia
Base tag:    v6.11.1 (qtmultimedia HEAD at the time of writing:
             43b808343682048d5170499217cf8a0f80e421aa, 2025-10-28)
Applies to:  src/plugins/multimedia/ffmpeg/qffmpegcodecstorage.cpp

Why: AV1 hardware-accelerated decode (via D3D11VA, at least on this
machine's GPU/driver) hangs and leaks memory rather than failing cleanly,
while software decode via libdav1d works correctly and quickly. Verified
directly with plain `ffmpeg.exe` outside of Qt entirely: `-c:v libdav1d`
decodes a real-world AV1 file cleanly (30/30 frames, no errors), while
`-hwaccel d3d11va` (letting FFmpeg pick the native hw-capable "av1"
decoder) never finishes and shows continuous, unbounded working-set
growth (65 MB -> 120+ MB over 10 seconds) for a clip that should decode
in a fraction of a second. This is very likely why the Qt Company's own
official FFmpeg build doesn't ship libdav1d/AV1 support at all -- across
the huge range of real-world GPU/driver combinations, enabling AV1
without very careful hwaccel fallback handling is a real stability risk.

Qt's own hwaccel device-type selection (HWAccel::decodingDeviceTypes(),
qffmpeghwaccel.cpp) has no per-codec granularity: it's a single
process-wide, statically-cached list read from
QT_FFMPEG_DECODING_HW_DEVICE_TYPES, applied uniformly to every codec.
Disabling hardware decode globally to work around AV1 previously
regressed H.264 playback in this project, so a codec-specific exclusion
is needed instead.

Fix: in isCodecValid() (used when building the cached decoder list),
reject every AV1 decoder implementation except libdav1d -- so the
hw-capable native "av1" decoder (and av1_qsv/av1_cuvid/av1_amf, if
present) are never even considered as candidates, while every other
codec's hardware acceleration (H.264, H.265, ...) is untouched.

To apply: cd <qtmultimedia source root> && git apply
patches/qtmultimedia-av1-hwaccel-disable.patch (or `patch -p1 <
...patch` if not a git checkout), then rebuild qtmultimedia (or all of
Qt) and Vivace.

